;;; Demo setup for regular Clojure REPL
rlwrap script/repl
(use '[cljs.compiler :as cljsc :only []] '[clojure.pprint :only [pprint]])
(def env {:ns {:name 'cljs.user} :context :expression :locals {}})
(defn js* [form] (->> form (cljsc/analyze env) cljsc/emit))
(defmacro js [form] `(js* '~form))

ul.li: Not a slick demo or an overview
Also not a complete in-depth study
3 of the collection types with literal reps
ObjMap for maps with string-like keys
String-like means string, keyword, or symbol
HashMap for maps with other kinds of keys (numbers, collections, etc.)
Like regular Clojure, built on the language's map type
These collections are built on CLJS protocols, while regular Clojure's collections are built on Java interfaces.
so what, how are protocols better?

li.pre:
rlwrap script/repljs
(ns cljs.user (:require [goog.structs.Map :as Map] [goog.structs :as gs]))
(def m (gs/Map. "foo" 10 "bar" 20))
(get m "foo")
(extend-type gs/Map cljs.core.ILookup (-lookup [this key] (.get this (name key))))
(get m "foo")
(:foo m)
m
(extend-type gs/Map cljs.core.ILookup (-lookup [this key] (.get this (name key)))
cljs.core.ISeqable (-seq [this] (map #(vector % (.get this %)) (prim-seq (. this (getKeys)) 0)))
cljs.core.IAssociative (-contains-key? [this k] (.containsKey this (name k))) (-assoc [this k v] (assoc (into {} this) k v))
cljs.core.IPrintable (-pr-seq [this opts] (pr-sequential (fn [[k v]] (concat (-pr-seq k opts) [" "] (-pr-seq v opts))) "<goog.struct.Map {" ", " "}>" opts (seq this))))
m
(assoc m "abc" 30)
; made possible by extend-type

; read:
(def form (read-string " (extend-type gs/Map cljs.core.ILookup (-lookup [this key] (.get this (name key))))"))
form
; eval, macroexpand
(pprint (cljsc/macroexpand-1 env form))
; eval, analysis
(cljsc/analyze env form)
